#, no-wrap
msgid "Instroduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "PAM (**Pluggable Authentication Modules**) is the system under GNU/Linux that allows many applications or services to authenticate users in a centralized fashion. To put it another way:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:27
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"> PAM is a suite of libraries that allows a Linux system administrator to configure methods to authenticate users. It provides a flexible and centralized way to switch authentication methods for secured applications by using configuration files instead of changing application code. \n"
"> \\- [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux_PAM)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "This document is *not* designed to teach you exactly how to harden your machine, okay? It's more of a reference guide to show you what PAM *can* do, and not what you *should* do.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "Authentication is the phase during which it is verified that you are the person you claim to be. The most common example is the password, but there are other forms of authentication.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "![PAM generalities](images/pam-001.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "The implementation of a new authentication method should not require changes in the configuration or source code of a program or service. This is why applications rely on PAM, which provides them with the primitives* necessary to authenticate their users.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "All the applications in a system can thus implement complex functionalities such as **SSO** (Single Sign On), **OTP** (One Time Password) or **Kerberos** in a completely transparent manner. A system administrator can choose exactly which authentication policy is to be used for a single application (e.g. to harden the SSH service) independently of the application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each application or service supporting PAM will have a corresponding configuration file in the `/etc/pam.d/` directory. For example, the process `login` assigns the name `/etc/pam.d/login` to its configuration file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\* Primitives are literally the simplest elements of a progam or language, and they allow you to build more sophisticated and complex things on top of them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "    A misconfigured instance of PAM can compromise the security of your whole system. If PAM is vulnerable, then the whole system is vulnerable. Make any changes with care.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "Directives"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "A directive is used to set up an application for usage with PAM. Directives will follow this format:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:52
#, no-wrap
msgid "mechanism [control] path-to-module [argument]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "A **directive** (a complete line) is composed of a **mechanism** (`auth`, `account`, `password` or `session`), a **success check** (`include`, `optional`, `required`, ...), the **path to the module** and possibly **arguments** (like `revoke` for example).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each PAM configuration file contains a set of directives. The module interface directives can be stacked or placed on top of each other. In fact, **the order in which the modules are listed is very important to the authentication process.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "For example, here's the config file `/etc/pam.d/sudo`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:62
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#%PAM-1.0\n"
"auth       include      system-auth\n"
"account    include      system-auth\n"
"password   include      system-auth\n"
"session    include      system-auth\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mechanisms"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "`auth` - Authentication"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:75
#, no-wrap
msgid "This handles the authentication of the requester and establishes the rights of the account:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "Usually authenticates with a password by comparing it to a value stored in a database, or by relying on an authentication server,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "Establishes account settings: uid, gid, groups, and resource limits.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "`account` - Account management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checks that the requested account is available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "Relates to the availability of the account for reasons other than authentication (e.g. for time restrictions).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "`session` - Session management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "Relates to session setup and termination:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "Performs tasks associated with session setup (e.g. logging),\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "Performs tasks associated with session termination.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "`password` - Password management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "Used to modify the authentication token associated with an account (expiration or change):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:98
#, no-wrap
msgid "Changes the authentication token and possibly verifies that it is robust enough, or that it has not already been used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:99
#, no-wrap
msgid "Control Indicators"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:102
#, no-wrap
msgid "The PAM mechanisms (`auth`, `account`, `session` and `password`) indicate `success` or `failure`. The control flags (`required`, `requisite`, `sufficient`, `optional`) tell PAM how to handle this result.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:103
#, no-wrap
msgid "`required`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:106
#, no-wrap
msgid "Successful completion of all `required` modules is necessary.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:108
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "**If the module passes:** The rest of the chain is executed. The request is allowed unless other modules fail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:110
#, no-wrap
msgid "**If the module fails:** The rest of the chain is executed. Finally the request is rejected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:112
#, no-wrap
msgid "The module must be successfully verified for the authentication to continue. If the verification of a module marked `required` fails, the user is not notified until all modules associated with that interface have been verified.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:113
#, no-wrap
msgid "`requisite`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:116
#, no-wrap
msgid "Successful completion of all `requisite` modules is necessary.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:120
#, no-wrap
msgid "**If the module fails:** The request is immediately rejected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:122
#, no-wrap
msgid "The module must be successfully verified for authentication to continue. However, if the verification of a `requisite`-marked module fails, the user is immediately notified by a message indicating the failure of the first `required` or `requisite` module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:123
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sufficient`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:126
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modules marked `sufficient` can be used to let a user in \"early\" under certain conditions:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:128
#, no-wrap
msgid "**If the module succeeds:** The authentication request is immediately allowed if none of the previous modules failed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:130
#, no-wrap
msgid "**If the module fails:** The module is ignored. The rest of the chain is executed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:132
#, no-wrap
msgid "However, if a module check marked `sufficient` is successful, but modules marked `required` or `requisite` have failed their checks, the success of the `sufficient` module is ignored, and the request fails.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:133
#, no-wrap
msgid "`optional`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/pam.md:136
#, no-wrap
msgid "The module is executed but the result of the request is ignored. If all modules in the chain were marked `optional`, all requests would always be accepted.\n"
msgstr ""

